---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does Cardinia Shire give a stormwater credit for permeable paving in Officer?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Cardinia Shire recognises permeable paving as an on-lot stormwater management measure under its Stormwater Management Policy and the Best Practice Environmental Management (BPEM) guidelines. It's not a flat-rate cash rebate in the way some metro councils run it - it's used to satisfy on-site detention (OSD) or permeable-surface requirements at planning and building permit stage, which can let you avoid expensive tank-based detention systems on tight Arena and Heritage Springs lots. The credit only applies when the install meets the Council's specified base, jointing and infiltration spec - a normal paver bed with sand joints doesn't qualify, and an engineer's certification is usually required for the credit to be applied at permit." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What permeable paving spec does Council actually require?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The standard infiltration-paver spec we install for Officer Council credit comprises: 80mm-thick clay-fired permeable pavers (or concrete-block permeable pavers with 8-10mm joints) over a 50mm bedding layer of 2-5mm angular aggregate, over a 100-150mm storage course of clean 20mm aggregate, over a non-woven geotextile fabric on the subgrade. Joints are filled with 2-5mm clean aggregate (NOT polymer sand - that defeats the purpose). The whole assembly is designed to detain and infiltrate the 1-in-10-year ARI rainfall event. On Class H reactive clay in Officer that means infiltration is limited, so the storage course often doubles as detention before slow discharge to the legal point of discharge." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does permeable paving work on Officer's reactive clay?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, but the design changes. On free-draining sandy sites permeable paving infiltrates straight into the subgrade. On Class H reactive clay - which covers most of Officer, Officer South and Heritage Springs - true infiltration is very slow (often under 10mm/hr after the clay wets up). We design Officer permeable pavements as detention systems: the aggregate storage course holds water during the storm event, then releases it slowly via a perforated outlet pipe to the legal discharge point. You still get the stormwater treatment benefit (filters out hydrocarbons, sediments, nitrogen) and the planning credit, but the engineering is detention-focused, not infiltration-focused." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often does permeable paving need maintenance?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Joint aggregate needs vacuum-cleaning every 12-24 months in Officer - typically by a contractor with a regenerative-air sweeper. The Officer growth corridor still has a lot of bare earth and construction sites blowing fines around, so the first 2-3 years post-install need more frequent cleaning. Once surrounding estates are landscaped and stable, intervals stretch out. We include the first cleaning service in our 24-month workmanship period at no extra cost so the credit-validating performance is maintained. After year 2, a typical residential vacuum-clean runs $250-$450 depending on area." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does permeable paving cost compared to standard pavers in Officer?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Permeable pavers themselves are about 25-40% more expensive per square metre than standard concrete pavers ($120-$160/sqm installed vs $90-$130/sqm standard). The bigger cost is the base - 200-250mm of clean angular aggregate plus geotextile and perforated outlet pipework adds $35-$60/sqm on top. So a typical Officer permeable driveway lands in the $155-$220/sqm installed range. But if the Council credit lets you avoid a $4,000-$8,000 in-ground detention tank on a small lot, the maths often works out cheaper overall - and you get a better-looking finish than an inspection-pit-and-tank arrangement." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Permeable paving in Officer - Cardinia stormwater credit & spec | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Permeable paving in Officer 3809 with Cardinia Shire stormwater credit. Class H clay detention design, infiltration paver spec, 24-month maintenance program. AS 3727 compliant."
  canonical="https://officerpavingco.com.au/permeable-paving-officer/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Permeable Paving &middot; Officer &middot; Cardinia Shire Credit</span>
      <h1>Permeable paving in <span class="accent">Officer</span> - stormwater credits, properly engineered.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Cardinia Shire recognises permeable paving as an on-lot stormwater
        management measure under its Stormwater Management Policy. Done right,
        it satisfies on-site detention requirements and can avoid expensive
        underground tanks on tight Arena and Heritage Springs lots. Done wrong,
        it&rsquo;s a normal driveway with extra steps and no credit applied.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book a free site visit</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">How the credit works</span>
      <h2>What Cardinia Shire is actually offering.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          Most homeowners hear &ldquo;stormwater credit&rdquo; and picture a cash
          rebate landing in the letterbox. That&rsquo;s not how Cardinia runs it.
          The credit is applied at planning and building permit stage - the
          Council recognises a properly designed permeable surface as
          contributing to your on-site detention (OSD) requirement. On a
          tight Arena lot where a conventional plan would force you into a
          $4,000-$8,000 underground detention tank, getting a permeable
          driveway over the line at permit can avoid that tank entirely.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Where the credit lives.</h3>
        <p>
          Cardinia&rsquo;s framework draws on the Victorian Best Practice
          Environmental Management (BPEM) guidelines for urban stormwater and
          the IPWEA permeable pavement specification. We&rsquo;ve been through
          this process with Cardinia&rsquo;s development engineering team
          enough times to know what they want to see on the engineer&rsquo;s
          stormwater management plan: infiltration test results (or detention
          calcs if the test fails), the paver product certification,
          base-course gradation curve, outlet detail, and a maintenance plan.
          We package all of that with our quote so your private certifier
          isn&rsquo;t chasing missing documents on submission day.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Class H clay reality check.</h3>
        <p>
          Officer sits on Class H to H1 reactive clay under AS 2870. Infiltration
          rates after the clay has wetted up are typically below 10mm/hr -
          well below the BPEM design rainfall intensity. So almost every
          Officer permeable pavement we install is a <strong>detention</strong>
          system, not an <strong>infiltration</strong> system. The 150-200mm
          storage course of clean 20mm aggregate holds the storm event water,
          then releases it slowly through a perforated outlet to the legal
          point of discharge. The treatment benefit (filters hydrocarbons,
          nitrogen, sediment) is the same. The planning credit is the same.
          The engineering language on the drawings is different.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Build spec</span>
      <h2>The Officer permeable pavement spec.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>Top down.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>80mm permeable pavers</strong> - concrete-block with widened spacers, or fired-clay permeable, with manufacturer certification of permeability under AS 3727 testing.</li>
          <li><strong>2-5mm clean angular jointing aggregate</strong> - never polymer sand, never standard washed sand. The joints are the inlet - block them and the system fails.</li>
          <li><strong>50mm bedding course</strong> of 2-5mm angular aggregate, screeded flat.</li>
          <li><strong>150-200mm storage course</strong> of clean 20mm aggregate, no fines, compacted in 100mm lifts.</li>
          <li><strong>Non-woven geotextile fabric</strong> wrapped around the storage course to keep clay subgrade fines out.</li>
          <li><strong>Perforated subsoil outlet pipe</strong> at 1:200 fall to the legal discharge - kerb-and-channel outlet, soakwell or legal stormwater point.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">2026 cost-per-sqm bands in Officer.</h3>
        <p>
          For straightforward residential permeable paving in Officer
          we&rsquo;re currently quoting in the
          <strong>$155-$220 per square metre installed</strong> range.
          That sits between plain concrete ($80-$100/sqm),
          exposed-aggregate ($115-$140/sqm), standard paver
          ($90-$130/sqm) and natural stone ($180-$280/sqm). The
          uplift is the storage course aggregate, the geotextile and the
          outlet pipework - not the pavers themselves. Where the Council
          credit avoids a detention tank, the homeowner is typically
          $2,500-$5,500 ahead on the total project budget.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">When permeable isn&rsquo;t the right answer.</h3>
        <p>
          We won&rsquo;t recommend permeable paving in Officer if: the lot
          falls towards the house (you don&rsquo;t want a wet detention
          course next to your slab), the existing legal point of discharge
          is uphill or unworkable, the proposed area sees heavy commercial
          vehicle traffic, or you simply don&rsquo;t need the planning
          credit because your lot already has working detention. In those
          cases an exposed-aggregate driveway with a grated linear drain to
          a soakwell is the better answer - same drainage outcome, simpler
          maintenance, lower up-front cost.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Maintenance &amp; warranty</span>
      <h2>Keeping the credit valid.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          Cardinia&rsquo;s credit isn&rsquo;t a once-off tick. The permeable
          surface has to keep functioning. If the joints clog with fines from
          surrounding bare lots, garden mulch or street sweeping, infiltration
          drops to zero and you effectively have a sealed paver driveway with
          poor drainage. Within the first 2-3 years post-install,
          while surrounding Officer estates are still being built out and
          dust is in the air, we schedule a 12-month and 24-month vacuum
          clean using a regenerative-air sweeper that pulls fines out of the
          joints without pulling the aggregate out with them.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Our standard inclusions.</h3>
        <p>
          We include the first vacuum-clean at month 18 in every Officer
          permeable paving job - no extra cost, no chase-up. After that the
          recommended cycle is every 18-24 months and runs around
          $250-$450 for a typical residential area. We hand over a
          maintenance log with the handover pack so when the home is sold,
          the next owner has documented evidence the credit conditions are
          being honoured.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Workmanship and product warranty.</h3>
        <p>
          24-month workmanship warranty on the install (joints, edge
          restraint, levels, outlet integrity). Manufacturer warranty on
          the permeable pavers runs 10-25 years depending on product
          - we&rsquo;ll spell out exactly which product, which warranty, on
          the quote. As a VBA-registered builder we hold the required
          Domestic Building Insurance and can produce certificates on
          request before any deposit is paid.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="cta-block">
        <h2>Free Officer permeable paving quote.</h2>
        <p>
          We&rsquo;ll do a site visit, check legal point of discharge,
          quote against the Cardinia Council credit spec, and provide an
          engineer&rsquo;s stormwater management plan ready for permit
          submission. No charge, no obligation.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="mailto:quotes@officerpavingco.com.au">Email quotes@officerpavingco.com.au</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
